## **Platform**

VuLink is a device used in water monitoring. It gets data from an instrument connected to it via a cable. Then it uploads that data to the cloud.

## **Audience**

USGS. Large mining operations. Municipal water departments. Other organizations that monitor water data.

## **My role**

I planned and developed print and online documentation. That means a quickstart guide that ships with the product. It includes a full PDF manual users can download from the company website. And it includes the online FAQs.

I also owned content design for the web and mobile app. I wrote the UI copy and decided on key terminology.

---

## **Project summary**

For years, In-Situ had been reselling another company’s telemetry devices. But those devices were riddled with setup and reliability issues. So In-Situ decided to manufacture its own telemetry. Their new devices would be easy to set up and would integrate seamlessly with the VuSitu mobile app.

## **The challenge**

Remote monitoring can be costly. Access to a monitoring site may entail a helicopter ride or hours and hours of driving. Setup needed to be easy. Users had to be sure they had done things right before leaving telemetry in place. **How could we make a reliable remote monitoring instrument that was easy to set up and could remain in the field for many months?**

## **The solution**

### Hardware

Our product manager had spent years talking with customers about their telemetry woes. He knew they wanted a device that was easy to set up. It had to provide clear signs the device was configured and working properly before users left the monitoring site. So we began the project with several well-defined requirements.![][image1]

Users would press a button to turn on the device. They would then launch the VuSitu app and wait for it to connect. The app would guide users through the short setup process. When it was complete, a light on the top of the instrument would indicate it was working as expected. LEDs would show the status of things like the cellular or satellite connection, battery, and memory.

### Software

One of In-Situ’s UX principles is *The product is the manual*. We wanted people to be able to configure and deploy our instruments with little to no documentation. To help make that happen for VuLink, I insisted on plain language. 

### Documentation

To support users, I created three forms of documentation. Each has its own purpose and format.

**Quickstart guide**  
According to Tesler’s Law, there’s a certain level of complexity you just can’t eliminate in a given product. That’s certainly true of a device as powerful as VuLink. It’s also why every In-Situ instrument ships with a quick-start guide in the box. So I developed one to help people get started with VuLink. It’s possible to set up the instrument by following this guide and nothing else.

I designed every In-Situ quickstart guide according to the following guidelines:

* Break processes down into easy steps.  
* Show *and* tell. In other words, include a picture with the instructions for each step.  
* Use plain language.

![][image2]![][image3]![][image4]

**User manual**  
Through interviews and tech support calls, In-Situ had learned that some users just have to have a manual for any product they use. They want comprehensive information about how it works, what it does, what can go wrong, and how to troubleshoot. I developed a manual for VuLink and published it on the company website.

**Online FAQs**  
After launch, our tech support and sales teams provided me with feedback from customers. They mentioned the questions people usually asked. I wrote and published FAQs with answers.

## **Process**

I was involved in the development of hardware and software as soon as the product manager   
handed off the initial requirements. Here’s a look at the overall process.

1. Brainstorming: Electrical engineers, mechanical engineers, software engineers, the UX designer, and I discussed the form factor and controls for the hardware.  
2. Hardware & software development: Engineers began designing and prototyping. I communicated daily with the team and built outlines of documentation.  
3. Documentation: As the instrument and software took shape, I worked with engineers and the product manager to flesh out the documentation and UI copy.   
4. Testing: We launched a beta test. I used feedback from beta testers to evaluate the quickstart guide and manual.  
5. Launch: VuLink went to market. I worked with the tech support and sales teams to publish FAQs based on common questions about the product.

## **Highlights**

## Battery hazards

One of the first challenges we experienced during development was quite serious. Incorrect battery installation would result in the instrument catching fire\! To prevent this, users would have to install three *new* batteries in the same orientation. They couldn’t mix old and new batteries or put one in facing the wrong way.

So I met with the UX designer to talk about how we’d make that clear. I made a graphic showing correct versus incorrect installations, which he turned into a sticker we would apply inside the device’s battery compartment. I also showed this graphic in the quickstart guide alongside a warning.

## Jargon: End of session

Early on, engineers referred to something they called “end of session.” I didn’t want that to show up in our manuals or software. By working with the engineers, I was able to translate it into a simpler idea. The end of session is when the instrument and the mobile app stop communicating with each other. So that’s how I wrote about it in the mobile app.

\[endSession.png\]

## Jargon: Reporting

A second terminology challenge involved how we talked about sending data to our web app. In stakeholder conversations, people used the noun “reporting.” I sensed a problem. We already had something called a report, which was a downloadable spreadsheet. And “reporting” was what users said when they talked about creating presentations with their data. I turned to plain language again. VuLink *uploads* to the cloud. So we would use the word “upload.”

\[upload.png\]

## Jargon: Downstream instruments

We encountered a third terminology issue when communicating about logs (the recorded data). Instruments that are connected to VuLink, which stakeholders called “downstream instruments,” can record data. VuLink can do that too. Each device stores the data in its own log. How would we make that clear? 

I asked tech support reps how users spoke about telemetry. They said people normally referred to “connected” instruments. So that’s what now shows up in the software and documentation. The mobile app also indicates whether a log is an instrument log or VuLink log.  
\[logs.png\]

## **Results**

VuLink quickly became the fastest-selling device in In-Situ’s 40-year history. It has also proven itself reliable beyond expectations.

Sales in the first year   
**400% of forecast**

Out-of-box failures due to user error   
**\~1%**

## **Retrospective**

It’s difficult, maybe impossible, to build a device as complex as VuLink without encountering some surprises. But the whole team learned from this experience. One of our biggest takeaways was that we needed to map out as many user scenarios as possible before development. Since the release of VuLink, In-Situ has been using story mapping to do just that.
